metadata.name: Bound #318
metadata.description:
Knots bind and hold, mark time, and unite. But the power of a well-tied knot isn't only to fasten – it also symbolizes how tightly one holds their pledges. Whether a commitment to a partner, community, or oneself – the longevity of a deeply held bond is often marked with a symbol of passing time, like knots tied in a rope.

Let these ropes remind us of the binds we hold – new ones, lengthy ones, unbreakable ones, and even those we’ve had to untie. In plain view, these knots invite us to contemplate what our bonds mean to us, and to see them anew.

metadata.name: Cosmic Type #128
metadata.description:
Cosmic Type is a kinetic type experiment that explores both graphic space as structural and semantic agency. Inspired by the early pioneering work of the concrete poets such as Dom Sylvester Houédard, Ian Hamilton Finley and Steve McCaffe, the project is a play with letters, words and graphic form in the computational and generative space.

Each iteration gives you the possibility to discover a variety of visual form through exploring the system. Please explore your iteration with the key interactions below. It is hoped that you give the time to explore and observe. If you don't, you may end up with just a blank canvas. 

Thank you for collecting. 

Key Interactions

‘a’ activates forward motion on/off
‘b’ activates backward motion on/off
‘r’ rotates grid 45° [ rotates on key pressed]
‘f’ rotates the grid freely [ stops on key release ]
‘p’ switches grid scale on/off [ this can be CPU heavy on older machines ] 
‘g’ extra glyphs on/off
‘q’ return to the initial state 


Program written by Mark Webster
Font is copyright ©simonrenaud

metadata.name: Pattern Grid  #70
metadata.description:
Recently I dove into Piet Mondrian's work. I've always been fascinated by his geometrical creations. So I thought I would make a humble homage to the Master, by offering my generative interpretation with a pattern twist. This design is the digital version of my pen plotter work, it regroups 3 editions in 1 NFT.

Features  : 
- 7 patterns with random subtitles variations
- 3 editions   : Dark *75% /  Light *24% / Blueprint *1%
- 18 color palettes 
- 2 color distribution : Even *75% / Random *25%
- Random tile amount

*Drop chance

Artist: Fabax
Date: 01/22

metadata.name: Ornamental typo #30
metadata.description:
Some time ago I was looking for inspiration in my local bookstore. In the secondhand section, I found this incredible book called Grammar of Ornaments. It features ornamental patterns from all over the world. However, the page about Pompeian patterns really caught my attention. It was a composition of patterns taken from different mosaics. A patchwork of patterns that normally don't belong together, yet in this instance looked far more interesting than each pattern taken separately.

So it was decided, I was going to make a generative piece based on this visual. I used a couple patterns as a main reference and took them for a spin. After enough iterations, new patterns started to emerge. In the same time something occurred to me. What would the people, who made the reference I used, think of what I'm doing? If I'm lucky they would think it's visually pleasing. But chances are they'd think I made mistakes / faux pas.

This helped me come up with the name of the piece :  “Ornamental typo”. It’s a homage to the reference material (The grammar of ornaments) and the realisation that the final result may not be approved by the masters that came before me.


Features (drop chance) : 

- Composition type (33%) : 3 types available ( Corner / Diagonal / Grid )  
- Palette primary (3.8%) : 26 palettes available
- Palette secondary (3.8%) : 26 palettes available
- Monochrome (50%) :  whether the primary color palette match the secondary one or not 
- Condition (25%) :  4 conditions that simulate the effect of time on the piece ( Mint / Near mint / Used / Old )


Export:

Click on open live, then :
-Press “1” to save as 2000*2000 jpg 
-Press “2” to save as 4000*4000 jpg

Feel free to reach me if you need to save your piece in even higher resolutions

metadata.name: a house divided #106
metadata.description:
This piece reuses the same line drawing algorithm from 'this is where i draw the line', meant to emulate a marker drawing on paper.

In terms of composition, we start with a single square, which we divide into two rectangles, either horizontally or vertically. We then repeat this process some number of times for each of the resulting rectangles. Finally, we fill the rectangles by drawing them with lines. These lines
can be either straight or curved.

The collection of inks and papers has also been expanded from 'this is where i draw the line'. Collectors of that piece have been placed on the reserve list as a thank you for their support.

This piece was created using p5.js

metadata.name: Random Piet #4
metadata.description:
When Mondrian and Theo van Doesberg founded the De Stijl movement, they wanted to explore the possibilities of geometric abstraction. 

Now that we generate art with code, geometric works are the most natural form to continue that exploration. The randomness is controlled by multiple parameters of which many are present in the features.

metadata.name: Context-Free Wind #134
metadata.description:
Context-Free Wind is a poetry generator and visualizer created by Ross Goodwin (https://rossgoodwin.com) in vanilla JavaScript without the use of any framework or external libraries, excluding code required by fxhash. The generator uses a custom context-free grammar algorithm and word lists assembled by the creator to produce (...admittedly, fairly strange...) sentences.

These sentences are then blown aloft by a procedural "wind" -- based on the algorithm Goodwin first explored in the following Dweet:
https://www.dwitter.net/d/23927

metadata.name: AutomataPunk, The Masquerader #492
metadata.description:
A playful spin on PFPs, and the prevalence of them on social media, especially among the NFT community.
The characters are procedurally generated, and then colored and texturized using 1D Cellular Automata.
Masqueraders hide their rarity scores. The cutest or most unusual one will be the most popular.
Their dimensions are always a multiple of 360.

Controls:
- Press 's' to save a PNG file.
- Press 't' to toggle, for a larger and higher resolution version that once complete can be saved as a 3600x3600 PNG by pressing 's'. In this mode, the Masquerader may become much larger than your screen. Wait for its render to complete before saving it. Toggle back to the regular size by pressing 't' again.
